{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-addf3d0ef7b5c625", "type": "tool_result", "content": "# On the Emotion Understanding of Synthesized Speech\narXiv: 2603.16483\nAuthors: Yuan Ge, Haishu Zhao, Aokai Hao, Junxiang Zhang, Bei Li, Xiaoqian Liu, Chenglong Wang, Jianjin Wang, Bingsen Zhou, Bingyu Liu, Jingbo Zhu, Zhengtao Yu, Tong Xiao\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_other\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Discriminative Speech Emotion Recognition (SER) models generalize poorly to synthesized speech, exhibiting a clear performance gap compared to human speech.\n  2. The dominant source of the synthesized domain shift is the speech token prediction stage, whereas subsequent flow matching and vocoder stages contribute substantially less.\n  3. Supervised and domain-adversarial fine-tuning fail to fundamentally resolve the generalization gap, indicating that existing SER models rely on non-robust shortcuts rather than capturing fundamental features.\n  4. Generative Speech Language Models tend to infer emotion primarily from textual semantics while ignoring paralinguistic cues, a behavior that persists even with prompt engineering.\n\nTags: Eval, Eval/听觉感知, LALM, TTS", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "6847692e-4f91-4cd0-afdc-9fa357533845", "uuid": "9febeb4a-a9de-44a4-85ab-84aca130ac84", "timestamp": "2026-07-15T13:48:44.365Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "# On the Emotion Understanding of Synthesized Speech\narXiv: 2603.16483\nAuthors: Yuan Ge, Haishu Zhao, Aokai Hao, Junxiang Zhang, Bei Li, Xiaoqian Liu, Chenglong Wang, Jianjin Wang, Bingsen Zhou, Bingyu Liu, Jingbo Zhu, Zhengtao Yu, Tong Xiao\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_other\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Discriminative Speech Emotion Recognition (SER) models generalize poorly to synthesized speech, exhibiting a clear performance gap compared to human speech.\n  2. The dominant source of the synthesized domain shift is the speech token prediction stage, whereas subsequent flow matching and vocoder stages contribute substantially less.\n  3. Supervised and domain-adversarial fine-tuning fail to fundamentally resolve the generalization gap, indicating that existing SER models rely on non-robust shortcuts rather than capturing fundamental features.\n  4. Generative Speech Language Models tend to infer emotion primarily from textual semantics while ignoring paralinguistic cues, a behavior that persists even with prompt engineering.\n\nTags: Eval, Eval/听觉感知, LALM, TTS", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-85ea7969acefcb12", "type": "tool_result", "content": "# Modeling and Benchmarking Spoken Dialogue Rewards with Modality and Colloquialness\narXiv: 2603.14889\nAuthors: Jingyu Lu, Yuhan Wang, Fan Zhuo, Xize Cheng, Changhao Pan, Xueyi Pu, Yifu Chen, Chenyuhao Wen, Tianle Liang, Zhou Zhao\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: audio_understanding\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We construct a Spoken Dialogue Reward Dataset (SDiaReward-Dataset) containing 11k preference pairs for training spoken dialogue reward models.\n  2. We introduce an end-to-end spoken dialogue reward modeling framework that decomposes evaluation into modality-aware and colloquialness rewards for multi-turn spoken dialogues.\n  3. We construct an episode-level spoken dialogue reward benchmark (ESDR-Bench) with multi-dimensional annotations and provide an empirical analysis demonstrating the superiority of specialized data-driven reward modeling over generalist judges.\n\nTags: Eval, Eval/学习, Eval/听觉感知, Eval/情感语境交互", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "6847692e-4f91-4cd0-afdc-9fa357533845", "uuid": "c2d86afe-9831-4326-9fa6-8857f176d50e", "timestamp": "2026-07-15T13:48:44.608Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "# Modeling and Benchmarking Spoken Dialogue Rewards with Modality and Colloquialness\narXiv: 2603.14889\nAuthors: Jingyu Lu, Yuhan Wang, Fan Zhuo, Xize Cheng, Changhao Pan, Xueyi Pu, Yifu Chen, Chenyuhao Wen, Tianle Liang, Zhou Zhao\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: audio_understanding\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We construct a Spoken Dialogue Reward Dataset (SDiaReward-Dataset) containing 11k preference pairs for training spoken dialogue reward models.\n  2. We introduce an end-to-end spoken dialogue reward modeling framework that decomposes evaluation into modality-aware and colloquialness rewards for multi-turn spoken dialogues.\n  3. We construct an episode-level spoken dialogue reward benchmark (ESDR-Bench) with multi-dimensional annotations and provide an empirical analysis demonstrating the superiority of specialized data-driven reward modeling over generalist judges.\n\nTags: Eval, Eval/学习, Eval/听觉感知, Eval/情感语境交互", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
