{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-af74ba49ff831549", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tAn Omnilingual-ASR-Based Speech-LLM System for the 2nd MLC-SLM\n2\tChallenge\n3\tShuming Fang1 , Shuifei Zeng2\n4\t1\n5\t\n6\t2\n7\t\n8\tUGREEN AI Lab, Shenzhen, China\n9\tSchool of Computer Science (National Pilot Software Engineering School),\n10\tBeijing University of Posts and Telecommunications, Beijing, China\n11\tsimon.fang@ugreen.com\n12\t\n13\tarXiv:2607.12468v1 [cs.SD] 14 Jul 2026\n14\t\n15\tAbstract\n16\tWe describe our submission to Task 1 of the 2nd MLCSLM Challenge: a cascaded diarization-then-recognition system that combines DiariZen-Large-s80 (WavLM-Large) segmentation, CAM++ embedding-based two-speaker clustering,\n17\tand a LoRA-adapted omniASR LLM 7B v2 recognizer, with\n18\tno oracle segmentation or speaker labels at test time. On the official Development set (150 conversations, 21 language/accent\n19\tcategories) the system attains a macro tcpMER of 29.27%, versus 79.15% for the official baseline; on the Evaluation set it\n20\tscores 50.23%. We also analyze two engineering choices that\n21\tsubstantially affect tcpMER. First, embedding-based speaker\n22\tclustering outperforms an end-to-end-style alternative that assigns speakers from ASR <sc> turn markers alone. Second,\n23\toverlap-aware segmentation, although intended to raise diarization recall, increases tcpMER because overlapped speech is\n24\ttranscribed twice.\n25\tIndex Terms: speaker diarization, multilingual conversational\n26\tspeech, speaker assignment, time-constrained evaluation, cascaded systems\n27\t\n28\t1. Introduction\n29\tConversational speech in realistic, multilingual settings remains challenging for both automatic speech recognition (ASR)\n30\tand speaker diarization (SD). The Multilingual Conversational\n31\tSpeech Language Model (MLC-SLM) Challenge [1] targets\n32\tthis gap by releasing a real-world, multi-language conversational corpus. In its second edition, Task 1 asks participants\n33\tto jointly perform speaker diarization (“who spoke when”)\n34\tand recognition (“what was said”) on raw recordings, without any oracle segmentation or speaker labels at evaluation\n35\ttime. Systems are ranked by the time-constrained minimumpermutation error rate (tcpMER), i.e. tcpWER for most languages and tcpCER for Japanese, Korean and Thai [2]; speaker\n36\tpermutations are resolved before concatenating transcripts for\n37\tscoring. The official Task-1 baseline fine-tunes Microsoft’s\n38\topen-source VibeVoice-ASR with LoRA on the challenge training set [3].\n39\tThis paper describes our Task 1 submission and the\n40\tDevelopment-set ablations used to select it. The system is a cascaded pipeline—neural segmentation, CAM++-based speaker\n41\tclustering, and LoRA-adapted ASR—so that each stage can be\n42\ttuned and compared under the official tcpMER protocol. The\n43\tremainder of the paper is organized as follows: Section 2 details\n44\tthe implementation, Section 3 the evaluation setup, and Section 4 reports Development results, component ablations (Table 3), and the Evaluation-set leaderboard score. In summary:\n45\tAccepted to INTERSPEECH 2026.\n46\t\n47\tRaw conversation\n48\t(no oracle SD/ASR)\n49\tDiarization front-end\n50\tFunASR FSMN-VAD → DiariZen-Large-s80 seg.\n51\tSpeaker assignment\n52\tpre-trained CAM++ embeddings → spectral clustering (2 spk)\n53\tRecognition\n54\tLoRA-adapted omniASR LLM 7B v2,\n55\tlanguage-constrained decoding\n56\tPost-processing\n57\t<sc> split + per-clause times, hyp. de-dup\n58\tSubmission hyp.stm\n59\tMain findings from component ablations. (1) Cascaded embedding assignment beats end-to-end <sc> assignment;\n60\t(2) DiariZen-Large-s80 segmentation yields the lowest tcpMER;\n61\t(3) overlap-aware segmentation hurts tcpMER.\n62\t\n63\tFigure 1: Overview of the submitted cascaded pipeline (top to\n64\tbottom) and the main outcomes of our Development-set ablations (Table 3).\n65\t\n66\t• We describe the final cascaded system submitted to the\n67\tchallenge (Exp4 in Table 3).\n68\t• We compare embedding-based clustering with end-toend <sc>-based speaker assignment on the Development set.\n69\t• We compare overlap-enabled and overlap-disabled segmentation fronts under the same scoring protocol.\n70\t• We report the Evaluation-set leaderboard score and discuss the gap to Development tuning.\n71\t\n72\t2. System Description\n73\tFigure 1 summarizes the pipeline.\n74\tA raw conversation\n75\tis (1) segmented into single-speaker regions, (2) assigned\n76\tspeaker identities by embedding extraction and clustering,\n77\t(3) transcribed segment-by-segment by the ASR model, and\n78\t(4) cleaned and packed into the submission format. The four\n79\tstages are decoupled so that each can be replaced and ablated\n80\tindependently.\n81\t\n82\t\f2.1. Speaker diarization front-end\n83\tWe build on the 3D-Speaker toolkit [4] with a cascaded layout: segmentation is handled separately from speaker assignment. This separation matches our implementation and makes\n84\tthe Exp1–Exp4 comparisons in Section 4 straightforward—\n85\teach stage can be swapped without retraining the recognizer.\n86\tVoice activity detection.\n87\tAll diarization configurations first apply the FunASR feedforward sequential\n88\tmemory\n89\tnetwork\n90\t(FSMN)\n91\tvoice-activity\n92\tdetector [5, 6], using the ModelScope checkpoint\n93\tspeech fsmn vad zh-cn-16k-common-pytorch.\n94\tVAD is a shared module in every inference run and is not part\n95\tof the segmentation-model comparison below.\n96\tSegmentation. On top of VAD we compare two publicly released neural segmenters, both integrated via the 3D-Speaker\n97\tpyannote.audio inference stack [4]: (a) the HuggingFace checkpoint pyannote/segmentation-3.0 [7, 8], a\n98\tPyanNet powerset segmentation model (SincNet + BiLSTM\n99\thead; 10 s windows, 10% hop) used as a segmenter only—\n100\twe do not use the pyannote speaker-embedding pipeline, and\n101\tinstead pair it with CAM++ clustering below; overlappedspeech decoding from the powerset head is enabled in Exp2\n102\tand disabled in Exp3; and (b) the DiariZen-Large-s80 checkpoint (BUT-FIT/diarizen-wavlm-large-s80-md), a\n103\tWavLM-Large + Conformer EEND segmentation model [9],\n104\trun with 12 s windows and a 10% hop (Exp4, submitted).\n105\tThe raw segments are post-processed by (i) dropping segments\n106\tshorter than 0.7 s, (ii) merging same-speaker segments separated by gaps ≤ 1.5 s, and (iii) splitting any segment longer\n107\tthan 25 s, which keeps the per-segment duration within the ASR\n108\tmodel’s stable input range.\n109\tSpeaker embedding. We use the publicly released, pre-trained\n110\tCAM++ [10] checkpoint from the 3D-Speaker toolkit [4]\n111\t(campplus cn en common): it is lightweight, supports multilingual telephone speech out of the box, and fits our twospeaker clustering stage without additional speaker-model training. For each candidate segment we slice 1.5 s sub-windows\n112\twith a 0.75 s hop and extract 192-dimensional embeddings\n113\tfrom an 80-dimensional log-filter-bank front-end.\n114\tClustering. All sub-window embeddings of a recording are\n115\tgrouped by spectral clustering [11] with the number of speakers\n116\tfixed to two, matching the two-party telephone conversations\n117\tof the corpus. Each candidate segment then receives a single\n118\tanonymous speaker ID (Speaker1/Speaker2), and adjacent same-speaker segments are merged. Because the DiariZen\n119\tfront-end can hypothesize concurrent speakers, a further postprocessing step resolves any residual cross-speaker time overlap\n120\t(the shorter segment yields the overlapped region), so the segments passed to the recognizer are effectively non-overlapping.\n121\t2.2. Multilingual ASR with LoRA adaptation\n122\tThe\n123\trecognizer\n124\tis\n125\tMeta’s\n126\tpublicly\n127\treleased\n128\tomniASR LLM 7B v2 checkpoint from the Omnilingual\n129\tASR family [12] (a wav2vec2-style encoder with a CTC head).\n130\tWe adapt it to the conversational, telephone-channel domain\n131\twith Low-Rank Adaptation [13] rather than full fine-tuning:\n132\twith a single GPU and a 7B backbone, LoRA is the only\n133\tpractical option, and freezing the acoustic encoder also guards\n134\ta strong multilingual model against over-fitting the comparatively small in-domain set. Only the low-rank adapters (rank\n135\tr=8, α=16, dropout 0.05) are updated, under a CTC objective.\n136\tAdaptation runs in fairseq2 for 50k steps with FSDP and\n137\tbfloat16; utterances are filtered to 2–15 s and length-bucketed\n138\t\n139\t(up to 4×105 audio elements per batch, gradient accumulation\n140\t16). We use AdamW (lr 2×10−4 , β=(0.9, 0.98), no weight\n141\tdecay) with a tri-stage warm-up/hold/decay schedule (ratios\n142\t0.1/0.4/0.5). All reported systems use the same 50k-step\n143\tcheckpoint. Training utterances are packed from consecutive\n144\treference-segmented turns in the challenge training set (oracle\n145\tboundaries available only during adaptation, not at test time)\n146\tsubject to the length filter; transcripts concatenate segment text\n147\tand insert a speaker-change token (<sc>) between adjacent\n148\tsegments from different speakers (but not between consecutive\n149\tsegments of the same speaker), so the model learns to predict\n150\tturn boundaries alongside lexical content.\n151\tAt inference, each diarized segment is decoded with the\n152\ttarget language supplied explicitly as a decoding constraint\n153\t(lang=<lang>), which confines the decoder to the target language’s token space and effectively eliminates spurious language switching.\n154\t2.3. Post-processing\n155\tTwo inference-time steps reduce time-constrained errors without changing the acoustic model. (1) Speaker-change splitting: the recognizer outputs the <sc> markers it was trained\n156\ton; within a segment we split on these markers and allocate\n157\tper-sub-clause timestamps proportional to character length, instead of sharing a single timestamp across the whole segment. (2) Repeated-hypothesis de-duplication: within a segment, near-duplicate sub-clauses (identical, substring, or ≥ 0.9\n158\tsequence similarity after NFKC + case folding) are removed to\n159\tsuppress decoder echo. All Development-set numbers in this\n160\tpaper, including Exp1–Exp4, are scored with the same official\n161\tsymmetric normalization applied to references and hypotheses (NFKC, then strict tokenization aligned with the challenge\n162\tWER/CER scripts, with punctuation removal for word cohorts);\n163\tsee Section 3.\n164\t\n165\t3. Experimental Setup\n166\tData. All results are reported on the official MLC-SLM Development set: 150 long conversational recordings (∼ 30 min\n167\ttelephone-channel sessions) spanning 21 language/accent categories (English is split into five accents, following the official\n168\tbreakdown). The final system is submitted on the Evaluation\n169\tset. LoRA adaptation uses the official challenge training manifest with reference turn boundaries (available for training only).\n170\tMetrics. Following the challenge, we report tcpWER for 18\n171\tcategories and tcpCER for Japanese, Korean and Thai, with a\n172\tcollar of 5 s computed by MeetEval [2]. For each cohort we report the micro rate (total errors over total reference tokens); the\n173\toverall macro score is the mean of per-category micro rates over\n174\tall 21 categories. All results reported in this paper—main results, Exp1–Exp4, and baseline comparisons—apply this identical scoring-time normalization (Unicode NFKC compatibility\n175\tnormalization, which maps full-width and other compatibilityvariant characters to their canonical forms, followed by strict\n176\ttokenization aligned with the challenge WER/CER scripts, with\n177\tpunctuation removal for word cohorts) symmetrically to references and hypotheses, so neither side gains from one-sided text\n178\tcleaning. The official baseline Development scores (Table 2)\n179\tare quoted from the released repository [3], where the authors\n180\tlikewise apply their text normalization 2nd.py (NFC,\n181\tlowercasing, punctuation removal) symmetrically to both sides\n182\tunder the same collar and tcpMER protocol; we do not re-score\n183\ttheir system. The ∼ 50 point gap to our 29.27% therefore re-\n184\t\n185\t\fTable 1: Per-language results of the final system on the Development set, following the official 21-category breakdown (English reported by accent). Japanese/Korean/Thai are scored\n186\twith tcpCER, the rest with tcpWER (micro, %).\n187\tLanguage\n188\t\n189\ttcpMER\n190\t\n191\tLanguage\n192\t\n193\ttcpMER\n194\t\n195\tSpanish (MX)\n196\tEng. (Australian)\n197\tEng. (Indian)\n198\tThai†\n199\tItalian\n200\tSpanish\n201\tEng. (Filipino)\n202\tPortuguese (BR)\n203\tRussian\n204\tUrdu\n205\tEng. (American)\n206\t\n207\t11.1\n208\t17.8\n209\t18.2\n210\t18.7\n211\t19.9\n212\t20.0\n213\t20.1\n214\t20.3\n215\t22.9\n216\t24.0\n217\t26.6\n218\t\n219\tEng. (British)\n220\tVietnamese\n221\tFrench\n222\tKorean†\n223\tTagalog\n224\tGerman\n225\tPortuguese\n226\tJapanese†\n227\tFrench (CA)\n228\tTurkish\n229\t\n230\t27.8\n231\t33.0\n232\t34.6\n233\t34.8\n234\t34.9\n235\t37.8\n236\t39.4\n237\t40.3\n238\t46.7\n239\t65.8\n240\t\n241\tWord cohort micro tcpWER (18 categories): 29.41\n242\tChar cohort micro tcpCER (3 categories): 27.38\n243\tMacro tcpMER (21 categories): 29.27\n244\t† scored with tcpCER. The five English accents average 22.2%.\n245\t\n246\tTable 2: Official 2nd MLC-SLM Task-1 baseline (LoRA-finetuned VibeVoice-ASR) per-language tcpMER on the Development set, as reported in the official baseline repository [3] (collar 5 s; tcpCER for Japanese/Korean/Thai, tcpWER otherwise).\n247\tFor comparison, our system attains a macro tcpMER of 29.27%\n248\tunder the same 21-category protocol.\n249\tLanguage\n250\t\n251\ttcpMER\n252\t\n253\tLanguage\n254\t\n255\ttcpMER\n256\t\n257\tEng. (American)\n258\tEng. (Australian)\n259\tEng. (British)\n260\tEng. (Filipino)\n261\tEng. (Indian)\n262\tFrench\n263\tFrench (CA)\n264\tGerman\n265\tItalian\n266\tJapanese†\n267\tKorean†\n268\t\n269\t77.39\n270\t81.50\n271\t67.60\n272\t63.36\n273\t72.12\n274\t83.39\n275\t78.56\n276\t84.23\n277\t78.16\n278\t81.46\n279\t81.33\n280\t\n281\tPortuguese\n282\tPortuguese (BR)\n283\tRussian\n284\tSpanish\n285\tSpanish (MX)\n286\tTagalog\n287\tThai†\n288\tTurkish\n289\tUrdu\n290\tVietnamese\n291\t\n292\t75.64\n293\t73.02\n294\t83.84\n295\t82.51\n296\t78.81\n297\t81.09\n298\t83.67\n299\t92.97\n300\t89.63\n301\t71.81\n302\t\n303\tBaseline average (21 categories): 79.15\n304\tOur system (macro, 21 categories): 29.27\n305\t† scored with tcpCER.\n306\t\n307\tflects architecture, not asymmetric normalization.\n308\tHardware. ASR LoRA adaptation was performed on a single\n309\tNVIDIA RTX 6000 Ada GPU.\n310\t\n311\tconversational, telephone-channel data.\n312\t4.3. Cascaded-system ablations\n313\t\n314\t4. Results and Analysis\n315\t4.1. Main results\n316\tTable 1 reports per-language results of the final system (DiariZen-Large-s80 segmentation + pre-trained\n317\tCAM++ + two-speaker clustering + LoRA-adapted\n318\tFollowing the official scoring\n319\tomniASR LLM 7B v2).\n320\tprotocol we report over all 21 language/accent categories\n321\t(English is broken down by accent). The system attains a\n322\tmacro tcpMER of 29.27%, with a word-cohort micro tcpWER\n323\tof 29.41% and a character-cohort micro tcpCER of 27.38%.\n324\tFor reference, the official Task-1 baseline—a LoRA-fine-tuned\n325\tVibeVoice-ASR recognizer [3]—reports a macro tcpMER\n326\tof 79.15% on the same Development set under the identical\n327\t21-category protocol; our cascaded system lowers this to\n328\t29.27%, a relative reduction of roughly 63%.\n329\t4.2. Comparison with the official baseline\n330\tFor context, Table 2 lists the per-language Development-set\n331\tscores of the official Task-1 baseline as released in the repository of [3]; the baseline is a LoRA-fine-tuned VibeVoice-ASR\n332\trecognizer evaluated under the same 5 s collar with tcpCER\n333\tfor Japanese/Korean/Thai and tcpWER elsewhere, with symmetric text normalization as above. Its scores are high across\n334\tthe board—no single category falls below 60% and the easiest cohorts still sit above 63%—yielding a 79.15% average\n335\tover its 21 language/accent categories. Using the same 21category protocol, our cascaded system reaches a macro tcpMER of 29.27%; even our hardest cohort (Turkish, 65.8%)\n336\tis comparable to the baseline’s single best category (63.4%).\n337\tThis gap indicates that the combination of a strong segmentation front-end, embedding-based two-speaker clustering, and\n338\ta LoRA-adapted multilingual recognizer is markedly more effective than a single fine-tuned speech-LLM recognizer on this\n339\t\n340\tTable 3 summarizes the main component ablations on the full\n341\tDevelopment set (150 conversations, macro tcpMER over the\n342\tofficial 21 language/accent categories). All four experiments\n343\tare scored under the same official protocol (NFKC + strict\n344\tsymmetric normalization, collar 5 s). Following the incremental ablation style of [14], each experiment adds or changes\n345\tone pipeline stage while keeping the same LoRA-adapted ASR\n346\tcheckpoint and scoring procedure.\n347\tExp1 is an end-to-end-style baseline: FunASR FSMNVAD cuts the audio, the recognizer emits <sc> turn markers, and speakers are assigned by alternating O1/O2 at\n348\teach marker—without neural segmentation or embeddingbased clustering. Its macro tcpMER is 141.2% (values\n349\tabove 100% are possible when insertions dominate under the time-constrained metric). Exp2–Exp4 replace this\n350\twith a cascaded design: a neural segmentation model\n351\t(pyannote/segmentation-3.0 or DiariZen-Large-s80)\n352\tfollowed by CAM++ embedding clustering with two speakers\n353\tforced. This change alone lowers tcpMER from 141.2% to\n354\t35.3% (Exp2), showing that speaker identity cannot be inferred\n355\treliably from turn markers alone. Within the cascaded family,\n356\tdisabling overlap-aware segmentation (Exp3, 30.6%) improves\n357\tover Exp2 (35.3%) because overlapped regions are otherwise\n358\ttranscribed twice; switching the segmenter to DiariZen-Larges80 (Exp4, 29.27%) yields a further 1.3 point gain. Exp4 is the\n359\tconfiguration submitted to the challenge.\n360\t4.4. Leaderboard submission and error analysis\n361\tUnder team name fangshuming, our Evaluation-set submission scored a tcpMER of 50.23%, markedly higher than the\n362\t29.27% macro tcpMER on the Development set. We ruled out\n363\tseveral formatting artifacts: speaker-ID style (1/2 vs O1/O2)\n364\tis score-neutral under tcpMER, and overlap is negligible on\n365\tEvaluation (only two overlapping segment pairs in 20,914 seg-\n366\t\n367\t\fTable 3: Incremental ablations on the Development set (macro\n368\ttcpMER over 21 categories; official NFKC + strict normalization). Lower is better.\n369\tExp\n370\t\n371\tSystem\n372\t\n373\ttcpMER (%)\n374\t\n375\tExp1\n376\tExp2\n377\tExp3\n378\tExp4\n379\t\n380\tEnd-to-end: VAD + ASR\n381\t+ pyannote/seg.-3.0, CAM++\n382\t+ overlap disabled\n383\t+ DiariZen-Large-s80 (repl. pyannote)\n384\t\n385\t141.2\n386\t35.3\n387\t30.6\n388\t29.27\n389\t\n390\tments). Although Evaluation references are not released and\n391\twe cannot analyze per-utterance errors, the observed behavior\n392\tsuggests that the remaining gap is likely due to domain shift:\n393\tthe Development set was used to tune pipeline hyperparameters, while Evaluation differs in speaker, channel, and language mix—especially on already difficult cohorts (e.g. Turkish, French (CA)). We also tried an automatic translation / “decode-switching” post-step, which degraded tcpMER because\n394\treferences retain code-switched words; it was not used in the\n395\tfinal submission.\n396\t\n397\t5. Discussion\n398\tOur Development-set ablations suggest three practical lessons\n399\tfor building systems under the challenge tcpMER metric:\n400\tOverlap-aware segmentation. Overlap detection is commonly\n401\tused to improve diarization recall but hurt our tcpMER score:\n402\tduplicated overlap regions are transcribed twice and count as\n403\terrors under a time-constrained metric. We therefore disable\n404\toverlap in the submitted system (Exp3/Exp4).\n405\tSpeaker embedding. Segmentation alone does not identify\n406\twho is speaking. On the Development set, <sc>-only assignment (Exp1, 141.2%) remains far above cascaded CAM++\n407\tclustering (Exp3, 30.6%); we keep a separate embedding stage\n408\tin the submitted system.\n409\tMetric optimization. Choices that improve diarization recall\n410\t(e.g. overlap) and choices that improve the challenge ranking\n411\tmetric are not the same problem; component choices should be\n412\tvalidated on tcpMER directly.\n413\t\n414\t6. Conclusion\n415\tWe presented our Task 1 submission to the 2nd MLC-SLM\n416\tChallenge: a cascaded system with DiariZen-Large-s80 segmentation, CAM++ two-speaker clustering, and LoRA-adapted\n417\tomniASR LLM 7B v2. On the official Development set it\n418\treaches 29.27% macro tcpMER (50.23% on Evaluation). Development ablations showed that (i) a separate embeddingclustering stage is essential compared with <sc>-only speaker\n419\tassignment, and (ii) overlap-aware segmentation should be\n420\tturned off for this metric. Exp4 in Table 3 is the submitted\n421\tconfiguration. These observations may help guide future engineering choices for multilingual conversational speech systems\n422\tevaluated under tcpMER.\n423\t\n424\t7. References\n425\t[1] B. Mu, P. Guo, Z. Sun, S. Wang, H. Liu, M. Shao, L. Xie,\n426\tE. S. Chng, L. Xiao, Q. Feng, and D. Wang, “Summary on\n427\tThe multilingual conversational speech language model challenge: Datasets, tasks, baselines, and methods,” arXiv preprint\n428\tarXiv:2509.13785, 2025.\n429\t[2] T. von Neumann, C. Boeddeker, M. Delcroix, and R. Haeb-\n430\t\n431\tUmbach, “MeetEval: A toolkit for computation of word error\n432\trates for meeting transcription systems,” in Proc. 7th International Workshop on Speech Processing in Everyday Environments\n433\t(CHiME 2023), 2023, pp. 27–32.\n434\t[3] alanshaoTT,\n435\t“MLC-SLM-2nd-Task1-Baseline,”\n436\tGitHub\n437\trepository, 2026, available: https://github.com/alanshaoTT/\n438\tMLC-SLM-2nd-Task1-Baseline.\n439\t[4] Y. Chen, S. Zheng, H. Wang, L. Cheng, T. Zhu, R. Huang,\n440\tC. Deng, Q. Chen, S. Zhang, W. Wang, and X. Li, “3D-SpeakerToolkit: An open-source toolkit for multimodal speaker verification and diarization,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2403.19971, 2024.\n441\t[5] Z. Gao, Z. Li, J. Wang, H. Luo, X. Shi, M. Chen, Y. Li, L. Zuo,\n442\tZ. Du, and S. Zhang, “FunASR: A fundamental end-to-end speech\n443\trecognition toolkit,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2023.\n444\t[6] Alibaba\n445\tDAMO\n446\tAcademy,\n447\t“speech fsmn vad zhcn-16k-common-pytorch,”\n448\tModelScope\n449\tmodel\n450\thub,\n451\t2023,\n452\tavailable:\n453\thttps://www.modelscope.cn/models/iic/\n454\tspeech fsmn vad zh-cn-16k-common-pytorch.\n455\t[7] A. Plaquet and H. Bredin, “Powerset multi-class cross entropy\n456\tloss for neural speaker diarization,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2023.\n457\t[8] H. Bredin, “pyannote.audio 2.1 speaker diarization pipeline: Principle, benchmark, and recipe,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2023.\n458\t[9] J. Han, F. Landini, J. Rohdin, A. Silnova, M. Diez, and L. Burget,\n459\t“Leveraging self-supervised learning for speaker diarization,” in\n460\tProc. ICASSP, 2025.\n461\t[10] H. Wang, S. Zheng, Y. Chen, L. Cheng, and Q. Chen, “CAM++:\n462\tA fast and efficient network for speaker verification using contextaware masking,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2023.\n463\t[11] T. J. Park, K. J. Han, M. Kumar, and S. Narayanan, “Auto-tuning\n464\tspectral clustering for speaker diarization using normalized maximum eigengap,” IEEE Signal Processing Letters, vol. 27, pp.\n465\t381–385, 2020.\n466\t[12] G. Keren et al., “Omnilingual ASR: Open-source multilingual speech recognition for 1600+ languages,” arXiv preprint\n467\tarXiv:2511.09690, 2025.\n468\t[13] E. J. Hu, Y. Shen, P. Wallis, Z. Allen-Zhu, Y. Li, S. Wang,\n469\tL. Wang, and W. Chen, “LoRA: Low-rank adaptation of large\n470\tlanguage models,” in Proc. International Conference on Learning Representations (ICLR), 2022.\n471\t[14] S. Ding, R. Rikhye, Q. Liang, Y. He, Q. Wang, A. Narayanan,\n472\tT. O’Malley, and I. McGraw, “Personal VAD 2.0: Optimizing personal voice activity detection for on-device speech recognition,”\n473\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2204.03793, 2022.\n474\t\n475\t\f\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "6847692e-4f91-4cd0-afdc-9fa357533845", "uuid": "0ba3b3d3-ae1b-450e-9326-0fd60c524fc5", "timestamp": "2026-07-15T13:51:10.527Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/2607.12468v1.txt", "content": "An Omnilingual-ASR-Based Speech-LLM System for the 2nd MLC-SLM\nChallenge\nShuming Fang1 , Shuifei Zeng2\n1\n\n2\n\nUGREEN AI Lab, Shenzhen, China\nSchool of Computer Science (National Pilot Software Engineering School),\nBeijing University of Posts and Telecommunications, Beijing, China\nsimon.fang@ugreen.com\n\narXiv:2607.12468v1 [cs.SD] 14 Jul 2026\n\nAbstract\nWe describe our submission to Task 1 of the 2nd MLCSLM Challenge: a cascaded diarization-then-recognition system that combines DiariZen-Large-s80 (WavLM-Large) segmentation, CAM++ embedding-based two-speaker clustering,\nand a LoRA-adapted omniASR LLM 7B v2 recognizer, with\nno oracle segmentation or speaker labels at test time. On the official Development set (150 conversations, 21 language/accent\ncategories) the system attains a macro tcpMER of 29.27%, versus 79.15% for the official baseline; on the Evaluation set it\nscores 50.23%. We also analyze two engineering choices that\nsubstantially affect tcpMER. First, embedding-based speaker\nclustering outperforms an end-to-end-style alternative that assigns speakers from ASR <sc> turn markers alone. Second,\noverlap-aware segmentation, although intended to raise diarization recall, increases tcpMER because overlapped speech is\ntranscribed twice.\nIndex Terms: speaker diarization, multilingual conversational\nspeech, speaker assignment, time-constrained evaluation, cascaded systems\n\n1. Introduction\nConversational speech in realistic, multilingual settings remains challenging for both automatic speech recognition (ASR)\nand speaker diarization (SD). The Multilingual Conversational\nSpeech Language Model (MLC-SLM) Challenge [1] targets\nthis gap by releasing a real-world, multi-language conversational corpus. In its second edition, Task 1 asks participants\nto jointly perform speaker diarization (“who spoke when”)\nand recognition (“what was said”) on raw recordings, without any oracle segmentation or speaker labels at evaluation\ntime. Systems are ranked by the time-constrained minimumpermutation error rate (tcpMER), i.e. tcpWER for most languages and tcpCER for Japanese, Korean and Thai [2]; speaker\npermutations are resolved before concatenating transcripts for\nscoring. The official Task-1 baseline fine-tunes Microsoft’s\nopen-source VibeVoice-ASR with LoRA on the challenge training set [3].\nThis paper describes our Task 1 submission and the\nDevelopment-set ablations used to select it. The system is a cascaded pipeline—neural segmentation, CAM++-based speaker\nclustering, and LoRA-adapted ASR—so that each stage can be\ntuned and compared under the official tcpMER protocol. The\nremainder of the paper is organized as follows: Section 2 details\nthe implementation, Section 3 the evaluation setup, and Section 4 reports Development results, component ablations (Table 3), and the Evaluation-set leaderboard score. In summary:\nAccepted to INTERSPEECH 2026.\n\nRaw conversation\n(no oracle SD/ASR)\nDiarization front-end\nFunASR FSMN-VAD → DiariZen-Large-s80 seg.\nSpeaker assignment\npre-trained CAM++ embeddings → spectral clustering (2 spk)\nRecognition\nLoRA-adapted omniASR LLM 7B v2,\nlanguage-constrained decoding\nPost-processing\n<sc> split + per-clause times, hyp. de-dup\nSubmission hyp.stm\nMain findings from component ablations. (1) Cascaded embedding assignment beats end-to-end <sc> assignment;\n(2) DiariZen-Large-s80 segmentation yields the lowest tcpMER;\n(3) overlap-aware segmentation hurts tcpMER.\n\nFigure 1: Overview of the submitted cascaded pipeline (top to\nbottom) and the main outcomes of our Development-set ablations (Table 3).\n\n• We describe the final cascaded system submitted to the\nchallenge (Exp4 in Table 3).\n• We compare embedding-based clustering with end-toend <sc>-based speaker assignment on the Development set.\n• We compare overlap-enabled and overlap-disabled segmentation fronts under the same scoring protocol.\n• We report the Evaluation-set leaderboard score and discuss the gap to Development tuning.\n\n2. System Description\nFigure 1 summarizes the pipeline.\nA raw conversation\nis (1) segmented into single-speaker regions, (2) assigned\nspeaker identities by embedding extraction and clustering,\n(3) transcribed segment-by-segment by the ASR model, and\n(4) cleaned and packed into the submission format. The four\nstages are decoupled so that each can be replaced and ablated\nindependently.\n\n\f2.1. Speaker diarization front-end\nWe build on the 3D-Speaker toolkit [4] with a cascaded layout: segmentation is handled separately from speaker assignment. This separation matches our implementation and makes\nthe Exp1–Exp4 comparisons in Section 4 straightforward—\neach stage can be swapped without retraining the recognizer.\nVoice activity detection.\nAll diarization configurations first apply the FunASR feedforward sequential\nmemory\nnetwork\n(FSMN)\nvoice-activity\ndetector [5, 6], using the ModelScope checkpoint\nspeech fsmn vad zh-cn-16k-common-pytorch.\nVAD is a shared module in every inference run and is not part\nof the segmentation-model comparison below.\nSegmentation. On top of VAD we compare two publicly released neural segmenters, both integrated via the 3D-Speaker\npyannote.audio inference stack [4]: (a) the HuggingFace checkpoint pyannote/segmentation-3.0 [7, 8], a\nPyanNet powerset segmentation model (SincNet + BiLSTM\nhead; 10 s windows, 10% hop) used as a segmenter only—\nwe do not use the pyannote speaker-embedding pipeline, and\ninstead pair it with CAM++ clustering below; overlappedspeech decoding from the powerset head is enabled in Exp2\nand disabled in Exp3; and (b) the DiariZen-Large-s80 checkpoint (BUT-FIT/diarizen-wavlm-large-s80-md), a\nWavLM-Large + Conformer EEND segmentation model [9],\nrun with 12 s windows and a 10% hop (Exp4, submitted).\nThe raw segments are post-processed by (i) dropping segments\nshorter than 0.7 s, (ii) merging same-speaker segments separated by gaps ≤ 1.5 s, and (iii) splitting any segment longer\nthan 25 s, which keeps the per-segment duration within the ASR\nmodel’s stable input range.\nSpeaker embedding. We use the publicly released, pre-trained\nCAM++ [10] checkpoint from the 3D-Speaker toolkit [4]\n(campplus cn en common): it is lightweight, supports multilingual telephone speech out of the box, and fits our twospeaker clustering stage without additional speaker-model training. For each candidate segment we slice 1.5 s sub-windows\nwith a 0.75 s hop and extract 192-dimensional embeddings\nfrom an 80-dimensional log-filter-bank front-end.\nClustering. All sub-window embeddings of a recording are\ngrouped by spectral clustering [11] with the number of speakers\nfixed to two, matching the two-party telephone conversations\nof the corpus. Each candidate segment then receives a single\nanonymous speaker ID (Speaker1/Speaker2), and adjacent same-speaker segments are merged. Because the DiariZen\nfront-end can hypothesize concurrent speakers, a further postprocessing step resolves any residual cross-speaker time overlap\n(the shorter segment yields the overlapped region), so the segments passed to the recognizer are effectively non-overlapping.\n2.2. Multilingual ASR with LoRA adaptation\nThe\nrecognizer\nis\nMeta’s\npublicly\nreleased\nomniASR LLM 7B v2 checkpoint from the Omnilingual\nASR family [12] (a wav2vec2-style encoder with a CTC head).\nWe adapt it to the conversational, telephone-channel domain\nwith Low-Rank Adaptation [13] rather than full fine-tuning:\nwith a single GPU and a 7B backbone, LoRA is the only\npractical option, and freezing the acoustic encoder also guards\na strong multilingual model against over-fitting the comparatively small in-domain set. Only the low-rank adapters (rank\nr=8, α=16, dropout 0.05) are updated, under a CTC objective.\nAdaptation runs in fairseq2 for 50k steps with FSDP and\nbfloat16; utterances are filtered to 2–15 s and length-bucketed\n\n(up to 4×105 audio elements per batch, gradient accumulation\n16). We use AdamW (lr 2×10−4 , β=(0.9, 0.98), no weight\ndecay) with a tri-stage warm-up/hold/decay schedule (ratios\n0.1/0.4/0.5). All reported systems use the same 50k-step\ncheckpoint. Training utterances are packed from consecutive\nreference-segmented turns in the challenge training set (oracle\nboundaries available only during adaptation, not at test time)\nsubject to the length filter; transcripts concatenate segment text\nand insert a speaker-change token (<sc>) between adjacent\nsegments from different speakers (but not between consecutive\nsegments of the same speaker), so the model learns to predict\nturn boundaries alongside lexical content.\nAt inference, each diarized segment is decoded with the\ntarget language supplied explicitly as a decoding constraint\n(lang=<lang>), which confines the decoder to the target language’s token space and effectively eliminates spurious language switching.\n2.3. Post-processing\nTwo inference-time steps reduce time-constrained errors without changing the acoustic model. (1) Speaker-change splitting: the recognizer outputs the <sc> markers it was trained\non; within a segment we split on these markers and allocate\nper-sub-clause timestamps proportional to character length, instead of sharing a single timestamp across the whole segment. (2) Repeated-hypothesis de-duplication: within a segment, near-duplicate sub-clauses (identical, substring, or ≥ 0.9\nsequence similarity after NFKC + case folding) are removed to\nsuppress decoder echo. All Development-set numbers in this\npaper, including Exp1–Exp4, are scored with the same official\nsymmetric normalization applied to references and hypotheses (NFKC, then strict tokenization aligned with the challenge\nWER/CER scripts, with punctuation removal for word cohorts);\nsee Section 3.\n\n3. Experimental Setup\nData. All results are reported on the official MLC-SLM Development set: 150 long conversational recordings (∼ 30 min\ntelephone-channel sessions) spanning 21 language/accent categories (English is split into five accents, following the official\nbreakdown). The final system is submitted on the Evaluation\nset. LoRA adaptation uses the official challenge training manifest with reference turn boundaries (available for training only).\nMetrics. Following the challenge, we report tcpWER for 18\ncategories and tcpCER for Japanese, Korean and Thai, with a\ncollar of 5 s computed by MeetEval [2]. For each cohort we report the micro rate (total errors over total reference tokens); the\noverall macro score is the mean of per-category micro rates over\nall 21 categories. All results reported in this paper—main results, Exp1–Exp4, and baseline comparisons—apply this identical scoring-time normalization (Unicode NFKC compatibility\nnormalization, which maps full-width and other compatibilityvariant characters to their canonical forms, followed by strict\ntokenization aligned with the challenge WER/CER scripts, with\npunctuation removal for word cohorts) symmetrically to references and hypotheses, so neither side gains from one-sided text\ncleaning. The official baseline Development scores (Table 2)\nare quoted from the released repository [3], where the authors\nlikewise apply their text normalization 2nd.py (NFC,\nlowercasing, punctuation removal) symmetrically to both sides\nunder the same collar and tcpMER protocol; we do not re-score\ntheir system. The ∼ 50 point gap to our 29.27% therefore re-\n\n\fTable 1: Per-language results of the final system on the Development set, following the official 21-category breakdown (English reported by accent). Japanese/Korean/Thai are scored\nwith tcpCER, the rest with tcpWER (micro, %).\nLanguage\n\ntcpMER\n\nLanguage\n\ntcpMER\n\nSpanish (MX)\nEng. (Australian)\nEng. (Indian)\nThai†\nItalian\nSpanish\nEng. (Filipino)\nPortuguese (BR)\nRussian\nUrdu\nEng. (American)\n\n11.1\n17.8\n18.2\n18.7\n19.9\n20.0\n20.1\n20.3\n22.9\n24.0\n26.6\n\nEng. (British)\nVietnamese\nFrench\nKorean†\nTagalog\nGerman\nPortuguese\nJapanese†\nFrench (CA)\nTurkish\n\n27.8\n33.0\n34.6\n34.8\n34.9\n37.8\n39.4\n40.3\n46.7\n65.8\n\nWord cohort micro tcpWER (18 categories): 29.41\nChar cohort micro tcpCER (3 categories): 27.38\nMacro tcpMER (21 categories): 29.27\n† scored with tcpCER. The five English accents average 22.2%.\n\nTable 2: Official 2nd MLC-SLM Task-1 baseline (LoRA-finetuned VibeVoice-ASR) per-language tcpMER on the Development set, as reported in the official baseline repository [3] (collar 5 s; tcpCER for Japanese/Korean/Thai, tcpWER otherwise).\nFor comparison, our system attains a macro tcpMER of 29.27%\nunder the same 21-category protocol.\nLanguage\n\ntcpMER\n\nLanguage\n\ntcpMER\n\nEng. (American)\nEng. (Australian)\nEng. (British)\nEng. (Filipino)\nEng. (Indian)\nFrench\nFrench (CA)\nGerman\nItalian\nJapanese†\nKorean†\n\n77.39\n81.50\n67.60\n63.36\n72.12\n83.39\n78.56\n84.23\n78.16\n81.46\n81.33\n\nPortuguese\nPortuguese (BR)\nRussian\nSpanish\nSpanish (MX)\nTagalog\nThai†\nTurkish\nUrdu\nVietnamese\n\n75.64\n73.02\n83.84\n82.51\n78.81\n81.09\n83.67\n92.97\n89.63\n71.81\n\nBaseline average (21 categories): 79.15\nOur system (macro, 21 categories): 29.27\n† scored with tcpCER.\n\nflects architecture, not asymmetric normalization.\nHardware. ASR LoRA adaptation was performed on a single\nNVIDIA RTX 6000 Ada GPU.\n\nconversational, telephone-channel data.\n4.3. Cascaded-system ablations\n\n4. Results and Analysis\n4.1. Main results\nTable 1 reports per-language results of the final system (DiariZen-Large-s80 segmentation + pre-trained\nCAM++ + two-speaker clustering + LoRA-adapted\nFollowing the official scoring\nomniASR LLM 7B v2).\nprotocol we report over all 21 language/accent categories\n(English is broken down by accent). The system attains a\nmacro tcpMER of 29.27%, with a word-cohort micro tcpWER\nof 29.41% and a character-cohort micro tcpCER of 27.38%.\nFor reference, the official Task-1 baseline—a LoRA-fine-tuned\nVibeVoice-ASR recognizer [3]—reports a macro tcpMER\nof 79.15% on the same Development set under the identical\n21-category protocol; our cascaded system lowers this to\n29.27%, a relative reduction of roughly 63%.\n4.2. Comparison with the official baseline\nFor context, Table 2 lists the per-language Development-set\nscores of the official Task-1 baseline as released in the repository of [3]; the baseline is a LoRA-fine-tuned VibeVoice-ASR\nrecognizer evaluated under the same 5 s collar with tcpCER\nfor Japanese/Korean/Thai and tcpWER elsewhere, with symmetric text normalization as above. Its scores are high across\nthe board—no single category falls below 60% and the easiest cohorts still sit above 63%—yielding a 79.15% average\nover its 21 language/accent categories. Using the same 21category protocol, our cascaded system reaches a macro tcpMER of 29.27%; even our hardest cohort (Turkish, 65.8%)\nis comparable to the baseline’s single best category (63.4%).\nThis gap indicates that the combination of a strong segmentation front-end, embedding-based two-speaker clustering, and\na LoRA-adapted multilingual recognizer is markedly more effective than a single fine-tuned speech-LLM recognizer on this\n\nTable 3 summarizes the main component ablations on the full\nDevelopment set (150 conversations, macro tcpMER over the\nofficial 21 language/accent categories). All four experiments\nare scored under the same official protocol (NFKC + strict\nsymmetric normalization, collar 5 s). Following the incremental ablation style of [14], each experiment adds or changes\none pipeline stage while keeping the same LoRA-adapted ASR\ncheckpoint and scoring procedure.\nExp1 is an end-to-end-style baseline: FunASR FSMNVAD cuts the audio, the recognizer emits <sc> turn markers, and speakers are assigned by alternating O1/O2 at\neach marker—without neural segmentation or embeddingbased clustering. Its macro tcpMER is 141.2% (values\nabove 100% are possible when insertions dominate under the time-constrained metric). Exp2–Exp4 replace this\nwith a cascaded design: a neural segmentation model\n(pyannote/segmentation-3.0 or DiariZen-Large-s80)\nfollowed by CAM++ embedding clustering with two speakers\nforced. This change alone lowers tcpMER from 141.2% to\n35.3% (Exp2), showing that speaker identity cannot be inferred\nreliably from turn markers alone. Within the cascaded family,\ndisabling overlap-aware segmentation (Exp3, 30.6%) improves\nover Exp2 (35.3%) because overlapped regions are otherwise\ntranscribed twice; switching the segmenter to DiariZen-Larges80 (Exp4, 29.27%) yields a further 1.3 point gain. Exp4 is the\nconfiguration submitted to the challenge.\n4.4. Leaderboard submission and error analysis\nUnder team name fangshuming, our Evaluation-set submission scored a tcpMER of 50.23%, markedly higher than the\n29.27% macro tcpMER on the Development set. We ruled out\nseveral formatting artifacts: speaker-ID style (1/2 vs O1/O2)\nis score-neutral under tcpMER, and overlap is negligible on\nEvaluation (only two overlapping segment pairs in 20,914 seg-\n\n\fTable 3: Incremental ablations on the Development set (macro\ntcpMER over 21 categories; official NFKC + strict normalization). Lower is better.\nExp\n\nSystem\n\ntcpMER (%)\n\nExp1\nExp2\nExp3\nExp4\n\nEnd-to-end: VAD + ASR\n+ pyannote/seg.-3.0, CAM++\n+ overlap disabled\n+ DiariZen-Large-s80 (repl. pyannote)\n\n141.2\n35.3\n30.6\n29.27\n\nments). Although Evaluation references are not released and\nwe cannot analyze per-utterance errors, the observed behavior\nsuggests that the remaining gap is likely due to domain shift:\nthe Development set was used to tune pipeline hyperparameters, while Evaluation differs in speaker, channel, and language mix—especially on already difficult cohorts (e.g. Turkish, French (CA)). We also tried an automatic translation / “decode-switching” post-step, which degraded tcpMER because\nreferences retain code-switched words; it was not used in the\nfinal submission.\n\n5. Discussion\nOur Development-set ablations suggest three practical lessons\nfor building systems under the challenge tcpMER metric:\nOverlap-aware segmentation. Overlap detection is commonly\nused to improve diarization recall but hurt our tcpMER score:\nduplicated overlap regions are transcribed twice and count as\nerrors under a time-constrained metric. We therefore disable\noverlap in the submitted system (Exp3/Exp4).\nSpeaker embedding. Segmentation alone does not identify\nwho is speaking. On the Development set, <sc>-only assignment (Exp1, 141.2%) remains far above cascaded CAM++\nclustering (Exp3, 30.6%); we keep a separate embedding stage\nin the submitted system.\nMetric optimization. Choices that improve diarization recall\n(e.g. overlap) and choices that improve the challenge ranking\nmetric are not the same problem; component choices should be\nvalidated on tcpMER directly.\n\n6. Conclusion\nWe presented our Task 1 submission to the 2nd MLC-SLM\nChallenge: a cascaded system with DiariZen-Large-s80 segmentation, CAM++ two-speaker clustering, and LoRA-adapted\nomniASR LLM 7B v2. On the official Development set it\nreaches 29.27% macro tcpMER (50.23% on Evaluation). Development ablations showed that (i) a separate embeddingclustering stage is essential compared with <sc>-only speaker\nassignment, and (ii) overlap-aware segmentation should be\nturned off for this metric. Exp4 in Table 3 is the submitted\nconfiguration. These observations may help guide future engineering choices for multilingual conversational speech systems\nevaluated under tcpMER.\n\n7. References\n[1] B. Mu, P. Guo, Z. Sun, S. Wang, H. Liu, M. Shao, L. Xie,\nE. S. Chng, L. Xiao, Q. Feng, and D. Wang, “Summary on\nThe multilingual conversational speech language model challenge: Datasets, tasks, baselines, and methods,” arXiv preprint\narXiv:2509.13785, 2025.\n[2] T. von Neumann, C. Boeddeker, M. Delcroix, and R. Haeb-\n\nUmbach, “MeetEval: A toolkit for computation of word error\nrates for meeting transcription systems,” in Proc. 7th International Workshop on Speech Processing in Everyday Environments\n(CHiME 2023), 2023, pp. 27–32.\n[3] alanshaoTT,\n“MLC-SLM-2nd-Task1-Baseline,”\nGitHub\nrepository, 2026, available: https://github.com/alanshaoTT/\nMLC-SLM-2nd-Task1-Baseline.\n[4] Y. Chen, S. Zheng, H. Wang, L. Cheng, T. Zhu, R. Huang,\nC. Deng, Q. Chen, S. Zhang, W. Wang, and X. Li, “3D-SpeakerToolkit: An open-source toolkit for multimodal speaker verification and diarization,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2403.19971, 2024.\n[5] Z. Gao, Z. Li, J. Wang, H. Luo, X. Shi, M. Chen, Y. Li, L. Zuo,\nZ. Du, and S. Zhang, “FunASR: A fundamental end-to-end speech\nrecognition toolkit,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2023.\n[6] Alibaba\nDAMO\nAcademy,\n“speech fsmn vad zhcn-16k-common-pytorch,”\nModelScope\nmodel\nhub,\n2023,\navailable:\nhttps://www.modelscope.cn/models/iic/\nspeech fsmn vad zh-cn-16k-common-pytorch.\n[7] A. Plaquet and H. Bredin, “Powerset multi-class cross entropy\nloss for neural speaker diarization,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2023.\n[8] H. Bredin, “pyannote.audio 2.1 speaker diarization pipeline: Principle, benchmark, and recipe,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2023.\n[9] J. Han, F. Landini, J. Rohdin, A. Silnova, M. Diez, and L. Burget,\n“Leveraging self-supervised learning for speaker diarization,” in\nProc. ICASSP, 2025.\n[10] H. Wang, S. Zheng, Y. Chen, L. Cheng, and Q. Chen, “CAM++:\nA fast and efficient network for speaker verification using contextaware masking,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2023.\n[11] T. J. Park, K. J. Han, M. Kumar, and S. Narayanan, “Auto-tuning\nspectral clustering for speaker diarization using normalized maximum eigengap,” IEEE Signal Processing Letters, vol. 27, pp.\n381–385, 2020.\n[12] G. Keren et al., “Omnilingual ASR: Open-source multilingual speech recognition for 1600+ languages,” arXiv preprint\narXiv:2511.09690, 2025.\n[13] E. J. Hu, Y. Shen, P. Wallis, Z. Allen-Zhu, Y. Li, S. Wang,\nL. Wang, and W. Chen, “LoRA: Low-rank adaptation of large\nlanguage models,” in Proc. International Conference on Learning Representations (ICLR), 2022.\n[14] S. Ding, R. Rikhye, Q. Liang, Y. He, Q. Wang, A. Narayanan,\nT. O’Malley, and I. McGraw, “Personal VAD 2.0: Optimizing personal voice activity detection for on-device speech recognition,”\narXiv preprint arXiv:2204.03793, 2022.\n\n\f", "numLines": 475, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 475}}}
